d his patient wife to intercede on his behalf. While pretending to have lost his old literary skills and even to be forgetting his Latin, in the Poems of Exile Ovid in fact displays all his virtuoso poetic talent, now concentrated on one objective: ending the exile. But his rhetorical message falls on obdurately deaf ears, and his appeals slowly lose hope. A superb literary artist to the end, Ovid offers an authentic, unforgettable panorama of the death-in-life he endured at Tomis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aComplaint poetry, LatinvTranslations into English. 0aComplaint poetry, LatinxTranslations into English. 0aEpistolary poetry, LatinvTranslations into English. 0aEpistolary poetry, LatinxTranslations into English. 0aExilesvPoetry. 0aExilesxPoetry. 0aPoets, LatinvCorrespondence. 0aPoets, LatinxCorrespondence. 0aPoets, LatinxHomes and hauntsxRomaniaxConstanța. 0aPoets, LatinxHomes and hauntszRomaniazConstanța. 0aPoets, LatinxHomes and hauntszRomaniazConstanța. 0aRomansxPoetryxRomania. 0aRomanszRomaniavPoetry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520931374.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles